 ----------------------------- TOP PICKS ------------------------------
 Prosumer Video Cameras from your Desktop Video Guide
 http://glclk.about.com/?zi=5/79f
 If you are looking to make a serious attempt at videography or wedding video, you may want to take a step up in camera quality. Most camera's on this page are priced between $2000 and $4000.
 1. Sony DCR-VX2000 3-CCD Camera
 It has been called &quot;the ideal event videography camera&quot; by many major camcorder review sites. It's also the camera I use. Why? Great sound pickup, an uncanny ability to shoot in low light situations, amazing picture quality, and quality craftsmanship you would expect from Sony. You can get one for about $2000.
 http://glclk.about.com/?zi=5/79c
 2. Canon GL-2 3-CCD Camera
 Canon put this one out to compete with the VX2000 by Sony (above). It has many of the same great features and more - excellent still image quality (1.7 megapixel), a 20x optical zoom lens, and great design. This camera is a solid contender andwill run you about $2000.
 http://glclk.about.com/?zi=5/79d
 3. Sony PD150
 This camera really pulls you into a new league of quality. It's separate audio channels and ability to pull in balanced audio through XLR connectors can really enhance the way you record sound onto video. It's larged-sized CCD's will also bring you to a new level in picture detail and clarity. You'll pay around $3000 for Sony's semi-professional camera.
 http://glclk.about.com/?zi=5/79e
